unraveling the mystery ♪

50
00:02:16,614 --> 00:02:18,513
♪ That all started
with a big bang ♪

51
00:02:18,514 --> 00:02:19,636
♪ Bang! ♪

52
00:02:19,637 --> 00:02:22,637
♪ The Big Bang Theory 11x13 ♪
The Solo Oscillation
Original Air D

53
00:02:22,638 --> 00:02:25,738
== sync, corrected by elderman ==
@elder_man

54
00:02:29,352 --> 00:02:31,720
Okay, how do you want
to play this?

55
00:02:31,722 --> 00:02:33,688
Do you want to pretend like
nothing's bothering you

56
00:02:33,691 --> 00:02:35,323
and blow up later,
or do you just want to be

57
00:02:35,325 --> 00:02:37,859
a maniac right now?

58
00:02:37,862 --> 00:02:40,929
Nothing is bothering me.

59
00:02:40,931 --> 00:02:42,798
Fine. Be that way.

60
00:02:42,799 --> 00:02:47,102
If you want to talk,
I'll be flushing my sinuses.

61
00:02:47,103 --> 00:02:48,936
Wait.

62
00:02:48,938 --> 00:02:50,606
I have a confession.

63
00:02:50,608 --> 00:02:53,307
When I berated Leonard,

64
00:02:53,310 --> 00:02:56,178
it was a clever ruse
to conceal the fact

65
00:02:56,179 --> 00:02:58,380
that I'm not
working on anything.

66
00:02:58,381 --> 00:03:00,882
Well, I think
I speak for everyone

67
00:03:00,884 --> 00:03:03,886
when I say, “No!”

68
00:03:03,937 --> 00:03:08,107
The truth is I have
nothing of interest to pursue.

69
00:03:08,109 --> 00:03:10,341
Well, maybe this is
the perfect opportunity

70
00:03:10,343 --> 00:03:13,178
to take some time
for yourself and refocus.

71
00:03:13,180 --> 00:03:16,247
I'm sure you'll find something
you're excited about.

72
00:03:16,250 --> 00:03:17,916
Thank you, Amy.

73
00:03:17,918 --> 00:03:20,318
I don't know what I'd do
without you.

74
00:03:21,239 --> 00:03:23,972
Hey, can I stay here?
Sheldon kicked me out.

75
00:03:23,975 --> 00:03:26,074
Well, is everything okay?

76
00:03:26,077 --> 00:03:28,776
Yeah. He just wants
some alone time to work.

77
00:03:28,779 --> 00:03:29,912
Fine.
Make yourself at home.

78
00:03:29,913 --> 00:03:31,447
Yeah. We were just about
to watch a little TV.

79
00:03:31,448 --> 00:03:32,548
You're welcome
to join us.

80
00:03:32,549 --> 00:03:33,782
Thanks. I'll be right with you.

81
00:03:33,783 --> 00:03:36,185
I just have to, uh,
do my neti pot.

82
00:03:45,696 --> 00:03:48,631
So what are you guys
gonna watch?

83
00:03:51,202 --> 00:03:52,835
Okay.

84
00:03:52,836 --> 00:03:55,270
Hey, uh, what do you think
we should open our show with?

85
00:03:55,273 --> 00:04:00,174
Uh, “Thor and Doctor Jones”
or “Let's Get Astrophysical”?

86
00:04:00,176 --> 00:04:02,244
I don't know. I think
we should start with something

87
00:04:02,245 --> 00:04:03,679
that gets them up on their feet.

88
00:04:03,680 --> 00:04:06,448
Maybe
“Sherlock Around the Clock.”

89
00:04:06,449 --> 00:04:08,783
Great, yeah.
Uh, let's give it a try.

90
00:04:11,756 --> 00:04:14,188
Halley's napping! Keep it down!

91
00:04:14,191 --> 00:04:15,924
Oh. Right. Sorry.

92
00:04:15,926 --> 00:04:19,294
It's cool.
We don't need volume to rock.

93
00:04:19,297 --> 00:04:21,462
Instead of blowing
the roof off this place,

94
00:04:21,465 --> 00:04:23,164
we can gently lift it off

95
00:04:23,167 --> 00:04:25,833
and set it quietly down
in the backyard.

96
00:04:26,737 --> 00:04:28,003
Okay.

97
00:04:28,004 --> 00:04:29,571
One, two, three, four.

98
00:04:31,441 --> 00:04:33,374
♪ Holmes said to Watson ♪

99
00:04:33,376 --> 00:04:34,977
♪ On Baker Street ♪

100
00:04:34,979 --> 00:04:36,612
♪ Come on, Doctor ♪

101
00:04:36,614 --> 00:04:38,547
♪ Time to move them feet ♪

102
00:04:38,549 --> 00:04:40,448
Sing it with us.

103
00:04:40,450 --> 00:04:42,450
♪ Sherlock, Sherlock ♪

104
00:04:42,453 --> 00:04:44,186
♪ Sherlock around the clock ♪

105
00:04:44,188 --> 00:04:45,653
We can't hear you.

106
00:04:45,655 --> 00:04:47,455
♪ Sherlock, Sherlock ♪

107
00:04:47,458 --> 00:04:49,657
♪ Sherlock around the clock ♪

108
00:04:51,828 --> 00:04:54,028
Nice going.

109
00:04:54,030 --> 00:04:56,030
Sorry. Sorry. I'll get her.

110
00:04:56,032 --> 00:04:57,900
One sec.

111
00:04:59,302 --> 00:05:02,071
You bought diapers, right?

112
00:05:03,239 --> 00:05:05,340
Be right back.

113
00:05:05,342 --> 00:05:07,643
Rock and roll!

114
00:05:10,381 --> 00:05:13,248
Okay. Scratch paper, check.

115
00:05:13,249 --> 00:05:15,316
Whiteboard, check.

116
00:05:15,318 --> 00:05:18,686
Chex Mix, check.

117
00:05:18,688 --> 00:05:21,789
And here we go.

118
00:05:23,160 --> 00:05:25,794
Oh, dang it.

119
00:05:25,796 --> 00:05:27,328
Hello, Mother.

120
00:05:27,330 --> 00:05:29,263
Hi there, Shelly.
You will never believe

121
00:05:29,265 --> 00:05:32,167
who I ran into
at the barbecue festival.

122
00:05:32,169 --> 00:05:34,737
I am right in the middle
of some very important work.

123
00:05:34,739 --> 00:05:36,739
I don't have time for this
right now.

124
00:05:36,741 --> 00:05:38,941
Then why did you
answer the phone?

125
00:05:38,943 --> 00:05:41,109
Because you raised me
to be polite.

126
00:05:41,112 --> 00:05:42,910
Now stop bothering me.

127
00:06:12,609 --> 00:06:14,842
Hello again.

128
00:06:14,845 --> 00:06:17,912
Who did you see
at the barbecue festival?

129
00:06:17,914 --> 00:06:19,881
Mr. Watkins.

130
00:06:19,883 --> 00:06:21,182
Really?

131
00:06:21,184 --> 00:06:23,551
You called me and interrupted
my work to tell me

132
00:06:23,554 --> 00:06:26,287
that you ran into somebody
you could plausibly run into?

133
00:06:26,289 --> 00:06:28,657
I'm sorry, Mother,
I really need to focus here.

134
00:06:28,659 --> 00:06:30,292
I will speak to you next week.

135
00:06:30,294 --> 00:06:32,494
Okay, sweetheart.
I'll talk to you then.

136
00:06:41,806 --> 00:06:45,039
I thought Mr. Watkins
moved to Florida.

137
00:06:45,042 --> 00:06:48,576
He did.
He was back visiting his son.

138
00:06:48,578 --> 00:06:50,746
Oh, gosh darn it,
that is interesting.

139
00:06:50,748 --> 00:06:52,513
Was it Tommy or Joe?

140
00:06:52,515 --> 00:06:55,017
I bet it was Joe, 'cause
he and Tommy had a falling out

141
00:06:55,018 --> 00:06:57,186
over that time-share.

142
00:06:58,354 --> 00:07:00,922
You guys do anything
fun after dinner?

143
00:07:00,924 --> 00:07:03,357
Well, actually Amy came
back over and we hung out.

144
00:07:03,359 --> 00:07:05,527
Did you know that we're both
spelling bee champs?

145
00:07:05,528 --> 00:07:09,131
We stayed up for hours
trying to stump each other.

146
00:07:09,133 --> 00:07:10,799
Who won?

147
00:07:10,801 --> 00:07:13,268
Oh, she thought she had me
with “appoggiatura,”

148
00:07:13,270 --> 00:07:16,537
but I shut that down
expeditiously.

149
00:07:16,539 --> 00:07:19,140
E-X-P-E-D-I-T-I-O-U-S-L-Y.

150
00:07:19,143 --> 00:07:21,275
Expeditiously.

151
00:07:21,277 --> 00:07:25,580
Wow. I bet that made Penny
take off all of her clothes.

152
00:07:26,984 --> 00:07:30,051
Put her pajamas on and
then go to bed early.

153
00:07:30,054 --> 00:07:32,020
At, like, 9:00.
Yeah.

154
00:07:32,022 --> 00:07:34,556
- Hey. - Hey.
- Hey.

155
00:07:34,557 --> 00:07:36,525
Oh, are we still on
for band practice this evening?

156
00:07:36,527 --> 00:07:37,993
Oh, shoot.

157
00:07:37,994 --> 00:07:41,028
I promised I would take Halley
over to Bernadette's parents.

158
00:07:41,030 --> 00:07:42,674
Dude, the gig is,
like, next weekend.

159
00:07:42,698 --> 00:07:43,700
I know.

160
00:07:43,700 --> 00:07:45,900
I'm sorry.
I really want to do this,

161
00:07:45,902 --> 00:07:48,402
but I just don't think
I have the time.

162
00:07:48,405 --> 00:07:51,140
Okay. I-I guess
I'll have to cancel.

163
00:07:51,142 --> 00:07:54,443
Toby Greenbaum will have to
become a man without us.

164
00:07:54,445 --> 00:07:56,878
Too bad, you guys
kill at bar mitzvahs.

165
00:07:56,881 --> 00:07:59,715
And other events that
people can't leave.

166
00:08:01,451 --> 00:08:04,419
I don't want to be the one
who breaks up the band.

167
00:08:04,421 --> 00:08:07,054
You know, maybe you should...

168
00:08:07,056 --> 00:08:08,857
think about replacing me.

169
00:08:08,859 --> 00:08:10,926
Okay.
I mean,

170
00:08:10,927 --> 00:08:13,962
I know it'll be hard since we...

171
00:08:13,963 --> 00:08:15,963
Oh, I bet Bert could do it.
He plays guitar.

172
00:08:15,965 --> 00:08:17,198
I'm gonna go ask him.

173
00:08:19,102 --> 00:08:23,806
I guess he forgot that
I play the cello.

174
00:08:23,807 --> 00:08:27,309
I-I don't think he did.

175
00:08:28,546 --> 00:08:30,479
Okay, I think it's ready.

176
00:08:30,480 --> 00:08:32,313
Should we put on
safety goggles?

177
00:08:32,316 --> 00:08:36,018
Well, the funnest fun
is the safest fun, so yes.

178
00:08:36,019 --> 00:08:37,152
Hey.

179
00:08:37,153 --> 00:08:38,186
Hi.
Hello.

180
00:08:38,188 --> 00:08:41,156
Oh, Amy, you're here... again.

181
00:08:41,157 --> 00:08:43,090
Yeah, Sheldon said he needed
another night to work,

182
00:08:43,093 --> 00:08:44,893
so I said I'd give him
some space.

183
00:08:44,894 --> 00:08:46,261
So what's all this?

184
00:08:46,263 --> 00:08:48,931
Well, Amy and I were talking
about old science fair projects,

185
00:08:48,932 --> 00:08:50,632
and how fun it would be
to recreate them.

186
00:08:50,633 --> 00:08:52,167
We're making hot ice.

187
00:08:52,168 --> 00:08:53,335
Mm-hmm. It's pretty cool.

188
00:08:53,336 --> 00:08:55,704
Nice one.
Yeah.

189
00:08:55,705 --> 00:08:57,038
Turns out we both

190
00:08:57,041 --> 00:08:59,807
did this as our science fair
projects in ninth grade.

191
00:08:59,810 --> 00:09:01,609
Do you remember any of
your high school projects?

192
00:09:01,611 --> 00:09:05,180
Uh, well, I remember
telling Jenny Runyon

193
00:09:05,181 --> 00:09:07,382
that I would teach her
how to flirt with boys

194
00:09:07,383 --> 00:09:09,017
if she put my name
on her project.

195
00:09:09,018 --> 00:09:13,287
I got an “A,” she got pregnant.

196
00:09:13,290 --> 00:09:16,191
Girls like you are why I had to
come straight home after school.

197
00:09:17,561 --> 00:09:20,162
Check this out.

198
00:09:22,566 --> 00:09:24,233
Wow, that's amazing.

199
00:09:24,234 --> 00:09:25,499
Mm-hmm.

200
00:09:25,502 --> 00:09:27,536
The crystallization is
an exothermic process,

201
00:09:27,537 --> 00:09:29,037
so the ice is actually hot.

202
00:09:29,038 --> 00:09:31,138
I won first place for this.
So did I.

203
00:09:31,141 --> 00:09:33,407
I threw Jenny's baby shower.

204
00:09:33,409 --> 00:09:35,777
Oh, hey, in seventh grade,

205
00:09:35,778 --> 00:09:37,311
I built a cobra wave.
You want to do that?

206
00:09:37,313 --> 00:09:39,715
Oh, we can come up with
a wave speed formula,

207
00:09:39,716 --> 00:09:41,984
and see how accurately
we can predict the amplitude.

208
00:09:41,985 --> 00:09:43,652
Wow, I didn't think
anything could top

209
00:09:43,653 --> 00:09:46,922
last night's spelling bee,
but here comes math.

210
00:09:46,923 --> 00:09:49,590
I'm sorry, we-we don't
have to do more experiments.

211
00:09:49,593 --> 00:09:51,560
Let's do something
we can all enjoy.

212
00:09:51,561 --> 00:09:54,128
Hey, uh, you want to watch
that show you like

213
00:09:54,130 --> 00:09:57,231
where people want to buy a house
and then they do?

214
00:09:58,101 --> 00:09:59,434
No, no, you guys do
your experiments.

215
00:09:59,436 --> 00:10:00,435
I'll go pick up dinner.

216
00:10:00,436 --> 00:10:01,369
Are you sure?

217
00:10:01,372 --> 00:10:02,537
Yeah, you're having science fun,

218
00:10:02,538 --> 00:10:06,108
and I don't want to interfere,
or watch you.

219
00:10:13,816 --> 00:10:15,950
Did I actually do it?

220
00:10:15,952 --> 00:10:20,122
I did. I did.

221
00:10:23,460 --> 00:10:25,761
The answer is one in 18 million.

222
00:10:25,763 --> 00:10:27,662
What is?

223
00:10:27,665 --> 00:10:30,999
The odds of you
running into Mr. Watkins.

224
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,402
Oh, Shelly.
I have bad news.

225
00:10:33,403 --> 00:10:35,803
Mr. Watkins passed this morning.

226
00:10:35,806 --> 00:10:37,672
Oh.

227
00:10:37,675 --> 00:10:39,807
Oh, I'm-I'm sorry.

228
00:10:39,810 --> 00:10:42,244
I know.
What are the odds of that?

229
00:10:42,245 --> 00:10:44,513
Call you back.

230
00:10:52,845 --> 00:10:54,778
Now let's
calculate the amplitude!

231
00:10:54,781 --> 00:10:57,014
All right!

232
00:11:02,589 --> 00:11:05,824
Sheldon? Sheldon? Sheldon?

233
00:11:08,527 --> 00:11:11,061
It's annoying
when you do it.

234
00:11:11,064 --> 00:11:13,163
I brought pizza.

235
00:11:13,166 --> 00:11:14,699
Oh, thank you.

236
00:11:14,700 --> 00:11:16,768
I have been working
pretty hard.

237
00:11:16,769 --> 00:11:18,036
I-I could use a break.

238
00:11:18,037 --> 00:11:19,537
What's that?

239
00:11:19,538 --> 00:11:21,572
Oh, yeah, that is an experiment

240
00:11:21,575 --> 00:11:24,142
to see how many parallelograms
I could draw

241
00:11:24,143 --> 00:11:26,110
while holding my breath.

242
00:11:27,214 --> 00:11:29,915
Is that where you blacked out?

243
00:11:29,917 --> 00:11:31,383
No, actually,

244
00:11:31,384 --> 00:11:34,551
that's where
I blacked out.

245
00:11:34,553 --> 00:11:35,954
And this?

246
00:11:35,955 --> 00:11:37,354
That is a list

247
00:11:37,356 --> 00:11:40,557
of all the different types
of natural disasters.

248
00:11:40,560 --> 00:11:42,259
“Fire-quake”?

249
00:11:42,262 --> 00:11:44,763
I made that one up.

250
00:11:44,764 --> 00:11:48,399
Which I shouldn't have,
because now I'm scared of it.

251
00:11:48,402 --> 00:11:51,069
Hey, I thought you were
working on actual science.

252
00:11:51,071 --> 00:11:52,537
I am.

253
00:11:52,538 --> 00:11:54,973
I'm trying to come up with
a new approach to dark matter,

